Forward target_compatible_with / tags through the mix_library macro.

The macro filters **kwargs to fixed allowlists and silently drops everything else, so a
`target_compatible_with` set on a mix_library reaches neither the `_mix_compile` target (which
resolves the Elixir toolchain), nor the `_mix_library_info` target (which carries the auto-added
`@hex_pm//:lib` dep), nor the generated `_mix_priv` target (which carries native priv artifacts).
Without it on those internals, a wildcard `bazel build //...` under the default (non-Elixir)
platform fails toolchain resolution - first on `<name>_compile`, then on `@hex_pm//:lib_compile`
reached via the info target's deps - or leaks native priv builds through `<name>_priv` instead of
SKIPPING the package as incompatible. Forwarding it to the generated targets makes the info/priv
targets *directly* incompatible, which prunes their deps before they are configured. B3
patch-in-place; lets the Elixir lane live in-graph yet stay scoped to the transition-wrapped
//server entry points.

--- a/private/mix_library.bzl
+++ b/private/mix_library.bzl
@@ -387,4 +387,6 @@
         "deps",
         "include",
         "ez_deps",
+        "target_compatible_with",
+        "tags",
     )}
@@ -398,4 +400,6 @@
         "deps",
         "srcs",
         "include",
+        "target_compatible_with",
+        "tags",
     )}
@@ -417,6 +421,8 @@
         _mix_priv(
             name = name + "_priv",
             priv = priv,
+            target_compatible_with = kwargs.get("target_compatible_with", []),
+            tags = kwargs.get("tags", []),
             visibility = ["//visibility:private"],
         )
         priv_target = ":" + name + "_priv"
